<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>🎓 What You Learned — Log Analysis</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="edu-page">
    <a href="/" class="back-link">← Back to Challenges</a>
    <img src="/images/logo.png" alt="EECS Girls Who Tech Camp" class="page-logo">

    <div class="edu-card">
      <div class="congrats">📋</div>
      <h1>Challenge 5 Complete!</h1>
      <p style="color:#9090b0; margin-top:5px;">Log Detective</p>
      <div class="flag-reveal"><%= flag %></div>
    </div>

    <div class="edu-section">
      <h2>📚 What You Just Learned</h2>
      <p>You practiced <strong>log analysis</strong> — one of the most important skills in cybersecurity. Server access logs record every HTTP request: who made it (IP address), when, what they requested (URL path), and what happened (status code).</p>
      <p>You also learned about <strong>Base64 encoding</strong> — a way to represent binary data as text. Base64 is NOT encryption (it's trivially reversible), but attackers sometimes use it to obfuscate data in URLs, cookies, or request parameters. You spotted a suspicious Base64 string in a URL query parameter and decoded it to reveal the flag.</p>
      <p>You also noticed that the suspicious IP (<code>10.0.0.55</code>) was trying to access sensitive paths like <code>/admin</code>, <code>/.env</code>, and <code>/backup.sql</code> — classic signs of an attacker probing for vulnerabilities.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="edu-section">
      <div class="real-world-box">
        <h3>🌍 Real-World Application</h3>
        <p>Log analysis is the backbone of <strong>incident response</strong>. When a company gets hacked, the first thing the security team does is examine logs to understand what happened, when, and how. Security teams use tools like <strong>Splunk</strong>, <strong>ELK Stack</strong>, and <strong>SIEM systems</strong> to monitor millions of log entries in real time and flag suspicious patterns automatically.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="career-box">
        <h3>👩‍💻 Career Connection</h3>
        <p><strong>SOC Analysts</strong> (Security Operations Center) monitor networks 24/7 and analyze logs to detect and respond to threats. <strong>Incident Responders</strong> are called in when a breach occurs — they're the cybersecurity equivalent of firefighters. These are high-demand careers with excellent pay, and many entry-level positions value curiosity and problem-solving skills over formal degrees.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="edu-section">
      <h2>🔑 Key Takeaways</h2>
      <p>1. Server logs are a goldmine of information for both defenders and investigators.</p>
      <p>2. Base64 is encoding (reversible), NOT encryption (secure) — never use it to hide secrets.</p>
      <p>3. Suspicious patterns in logs — like probing for <code>/admin</code>, <code>/.env</code>, <code>/backup.sql</code> — are red flags for an attack.</p>
      <p>4. Pattern recognition and attention to detail are superpowers in cybersecurity.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="next-btns">
      <a href="/" class="next-btn secondary">← All Challenges</a>
      <% if (hasNext) { %>
      <a href="/challenge/<%= nextNum %>" class="next-btn">Next Challenge →</a>
      <% } %>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
